entry.title: Fix WebUI navigation starting while an about:blank navigation is pending commit.
entry.content:
https://crrev.com/c/4932625 changed the check that determines whether

a WebUI navigation can reuse an initial RenderFrameHost from using

!has_committed_any_navigation() to is_initial_empty_document(), to

avoid WebUI reusing the initial RFH after crashes (since

has_committed_any_navigation() is reset after crashes) and after

document.open() (which could inject content into the initial

document). Unfortunately, this inadvertently opened up a window for

races, since has_committed_any_navigation() becomes true after the

very first navigation passes ready-to-commit stage and sends out a

CommitNavigation IPC, whereas is_initial_empty_document() becomes

false only after receiving DidCommitNavigation. Thus, WebUI could now

try to reuse an initial RFH that has a pending commit about:blank

navigation, which would run into a failed CHECK in

RenderFrameHostManager::CreateWebUIForNavigationIfNeeded(), which uses

has_committed_any_navigation(). As a result, several ChromeOS WebUI

tests that do about:blank navigations in new WebContents followed by

WebUI navigations became flaky. Note that this only affects pending

commit about:blank (or other empty scheme) navigations, since other

navigations would reset IsUnused() at ready-to-commit time, which the

WebUI reuse also checks.



To fix this, the WebUI initial RFH reuse code now checks both

!has_committed_any_navigation() and is_initial_empty_document(), which

should handle all the involved cases. A test for the pending commit

race is also added, and the flaky tests are re-enabled.

entry.title: Show placeholder value when previewing empty fields.
entry.content:
Initially suggested values were hidden/shown based on whether the

underlying value is empty or not. crrev.com/c/4769360 changed this so

that we check whether the underlying value is null or not, so that

Autofill could sometimes preview empty fields.



Consider a field and Autofill offers

the user to fill the value "Bar" into that field. Before the user

accepts this suggestion, Autofill displays the suggested value Bar in

the field. The new Undo Autofill feature enables the user to revert

the field's value to the empty value. In that case, the suggested

value is the empty string. When previewing this empty string, the

placeholder should be visible.



The solution is to let only the "visibility" of the placeholder

"element" depend on the nullity of the suggested value, but all other

attributes (value or style properties) will depend on its emptiness.



This CL:

-Fixes the mentioned problem by letting the placeholder visibility vis a

vis the suggested value depend on the nullity of the value and not its

emptiness.

- Removes unused functions that are supposed to be used for placeholder

visibility but aren't

entry.content:
UserScript objects need to be marked as enabled in incognito in

order to inject in incognito processes. This is properly done for

manifest-specified content scripts and newly-registered dynamic

content scripts, but is not properly set when loading dynamic content

scripts from storage or for the new userScripts API.

SerializedUserScript so that it applies to all these sites

appropriately.



The right fix for this is to really pull incognito enablement off

but that's a bit of a larger fix.

entry.title: [dpwa] Fix the bug that existing tests are replaced just because of the
entry.content:
name change.



In the original change, both test id, which is equivalent to the test steps, and test name are used to determine if a test should be deleted / added.

kept. But this causes a huge problem when new tests are generated

be updated to the new one.

not impacted and the new tests will have the new naming convention.



This CL also fixed a small issue that test id is incorrectly generated when the code

of an action spans over 1 line. This is because `\n` is used to

breakdown the test steps.

entry.content:
Some APIs are restricted to the user being in developer mode. When

the user's dev mode state changes, the renderers are notified.

However, the bindings weren't being properly updated in these cases,

which meant that extensions wouldn't be able to access newly-granted

APIs if the user enabled dev mode for an existing renderer.



Fix this by properly updating the bindings in this case. Note that

this involves invalidating the bindings feature cache, since that

cache tracks developer-mode restricted bindings, which may have

changed.



Add new tests to cover these cases.

entry.title: Add response flag for hash-based code caching
entry.content:
Webview controls provide methods to intercept http(s) requests from the

embedded webpage and return arbitrary content. Some applications use

that functionality to load scripts, such as by returning the contents of

a local file from the app's installation directory. Such scripts are not

eligible for code caching, because the render process has no way to

determine whether the loaded script text exactly matches the text from

some previous load.



We already have code that solves the same problem for WebUI scripts: it

includes a cryptographically secure hash of the script's text when

saving the code cache data, and checks that hash when loading. This

allows the benefits of code caching, even for requests which bypass the

network cache and thus can't rely on response time as an indication of

content equality.



This change adds a new flag on URLResponseHead which tells the renderer

process to use the content hashing strategy for code caching on http(s)

requests (which would otherwise rely on the response time for judging

content equality). If the browser process sets this flag on responses

from webview interceptions (not implemented in this CL), then

webview-based applications can benefit from code caching.

entry.title: [image search] Fix the bug that image filepath does not elide
entry.content:
Originally the container of the image metadata does not bound the

children, that is, the children labels can extend to their maximum

width so that the elision won't occur.

This cl fixed that by changing the layout manager of the info

container to use two flex layout instead of one table layout. This is

basically because there is no good way to restrict the children's

bounds of the container using table layout. The flex weight is set to

adjust the child bounds if needed.



Two vertical layouts are used instead of 4 horizontal layout to

easily align the titles and the contents. Another reason is that the

title columns is considered to be removed in the future so this makes

the change easier.



Also this cl updates the typography of the content label to match

the spec.

entry.title: [Extensions] Un-mark `debugger` API as restricted to dev mode
entry.content:
While developing the feature to restrict APIs to users in dev mode,

we used the `debugger` API as an initial test API. This would be

restricted if and only if the base::Feature was enabled (and the

feature is currently off). However, we'll likely ship this restriction

with the upcoming `userScripts` API, which means we'll enable the

underlying feature to control dev mode restrictions.



In preparation for this, swap the tests for the general capability

to restrict APIs to dev mode from testing with the `debugger` API to

using the `userScripts` API. This way, we can enable the feature

without affecting any existing extensions of the debugger API.



This CL unmarks the `debugger` API as being restricted to dev mode

and updates all corresponding tests to instead use `userScripts`.

entry.title: iwa: Implement the installed IWA file structure.
entry.content:
Now we are copying the file that we intend to install into profile

directory. We create the 'iwa' directory in the profile dir and there

create a randomly named directory to store the signed web bundle there.



The caller is responsible to delete the original .swbn file

(if necessary).



So far it works for InstalledBundle only.



This CL introduces the concept of the .swbn ownership: is the file is

owned by Chrome, then Chrome is responsible for removing the file

on uninstallation or failed installation.



The success status of the install and prepare update commands now

include the IsolatedWebAppLocation to the place where the installed

.swbn is located.



Future work:

- remove files if pending update fails

- add garbage collection for failed deletions

entry.content:
The Storage Access API provides access to unpartitioned cookies in

third-party contexts. This CL is part of a series to extend that access

to non-cookie storage/communication mechanisms.



This CL only includes local/session storage as a starting place for

the new access. We want to be deliberate adding new mechanisms

since we need good testing and security review here.



All access is restricted to experimental contexts for now, no stable

access or origin trial timeline has been published.



Explainer:

https://arichiv.github.io/saa-non-cookie-storage/



Intent to Prototype:

https://groups.google.com/a/chromium.org/g/blink-dev/c/inRN8tI49O0



Part 1: local/session storage

Part 2: indexeddb

Part 3: web locks

Part 4: cache storage

Part 5: origin private file system

Part 6: quota

Part 7+: blob storage, broadcast channel, shared worker

entry.title: base/threading: Set ChromeOS display and compositing threads to RT
entry.content:
Using RT in Chrome shows significant performance improvements. Example,

mouse latency with a 49 person meeting test on Octopus shows a drop of

207ms to 95ms (a 54% improvement).



Add support to set display and main renderer threads to RT behind a

feature flag. We will enable finch experiments once kernel support for a

'safer form of RT throttling' is available in ChromeOS kernels [1] and

safely roll this out.



History:

RT is known to be problematic due to throttling for CPU bound workloads.

Disabling RT_GROUP_SCHED improved things a lot last year since

RT-throttling code breaks with that. We have been attempting to rewrite

throttling and discuss it with upstream and conferences. It looks like

the final direction that is going in is [1] and those patches are

(almost) in good shape.



[1] https://lore.kernel.org/all/cover.1693510979.git.bristot@kernel.org/



Bug: b/262267726, b/307274377

bypass completion.

subprocess termination) and the resulting route teardown on one thread

races with bridge bypass on another.



Since forced route teardown cleans up all the same objects and more,

we can simply terminate bridge bypass early in such cases.
